<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIMI VALLEY SCHOOL CHIEF TO RESIGN; 
</P>
<P>
EDUCATION: JOHN DUNCAN SAYS HE WILL TAKE OVER THE TOP SPOT AT A NORTHERN 
CALIFORNIA DISTRICT IN THE FALL. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supt. John Duncan of the financially troubled Simi Valley Unified School 
District said Friday that he will resign this fall to take over as chief 
administrator of a Northern California district. 
</P>
<P>
Duncan, who has headed Ventura County's largest school district for 16 years, 
said his resignation will become effective Sept. 16. He said he has accepted 
the position of superintendent of the San Ramon Valley Unified School District 
in Contra Costa County, near Oakland. The job will pay $98,900, a year, about 
$2,000 more than what he makes in Simi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been in Simi Valley for 16 years," Duncan said. "Simi Valley has been 
awfully good to me. But I'm ready for a new challenge." 
</P>
<P>
Duncan, 57, said the district's struggle to offset an estimated $8-million 
budget shortfall next year did not enter into his decision to leave the 
18,000-student district. The budget crunch has forced district officials to lay 
off 32 temporary teachers, four librarians and four nurses at some of its 26 
campuses. Dozens of administrators were also reassigned to lower-level 
positions with reduced salaries. 
</P>
<P>
"Over the last five months, it's been very difficult . . . but it's very much 
like any other school district," said Duncan, who has been the subject of much 
criticism from teachers and union officials because of the cost-cutting 
measures. "They all have budget problems." 
</P>
<P>
Duncan said one reason he decided to leave Simi Valley is that several of his 
children live in the Bay Area. Another, he said, was the pay increase. 
</P>
<P>
He said he informed members of the Board of Education about his decision during 
a closed session Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
"We'll miss him and his outstanding leadership," board President Helen Beebe 
said. "He has left us a real heritage." 
</P>
<P>
Beebe also dismissed any notions that the district's budget problems had 
anything to do with Duncan's decision to leave. 
</P>
<P>
School officials have attributed a large part of the district's financial 
problems to a lack of state money, due to an expected $3.6-billion shortfall in 
the state budget next year. Officials also blame a declining student enrollment 
and an 8% salary increase for teachers this year for contributing to the 
district's financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the district's 800 teachers and their union representatives, however, 
have accused Duncan and other district administrators of failing to adequately 
plan ahead to avoid major cuts. They have said it is unfair to blame the 
teachers' salary increase for the budget problems when Duncan and other 
district administrators are among the highest paid school officials in Ventura 
and Los Angeles counties. 
</P>
<P>
Bill Davenport, president of the Simi Valley Educators Assn., and several other 
top-level union officials are attending an out-of-state educators conference 
this week and could not be reached for comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Beebe said district officials will talk to several consulting groups to assist 
them in their search for a new superintendent. She said if a new administrator 
is not in place by September, an acting superintendent would be appointed to 
serve in the interim. 
</P>
<P>
Supt. William Streshly of the San Ramon Valley Unified School District said his 
district is slightly smaller than the Simi Valley system, with 16,000 students 
and 23 campuses, but that it is growing fast. Streshly said he is leaving the 
district to take a teaching position at San Diego State. 
</P>
<P>
San Ramon Unified has had its share of problems this year. Streshly said the 
district's 800 teachers participated in three wildcat strikes over a two-week 
period in April and May during union contract negotiations. He said the 
teachers had been demanding a 7% salary increase for next year but finally had 
to settle for a 3.5% raise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, John Duncan 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
