<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEEN-AGER ADMITS ABANDONING INFANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD A. OPPEL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A National City woman came forward Friday to say she is the mother of a newborn 
baby found rolled in a blanket beside a National City Pizza Hut on June 29. 
</P>
<P>
Jennifer Lynn Huggins, 18, an employee of the Pizza Hut, was booked into County 
Jail at Las Colinas on charges of felony child abuse and felony child 
endangerment Friday afternoon. She had turned herself in at the National City 
police station at 2:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
"She said she was unable to cope with the child and had not told anyone of the 
pregnancy," said Olivia Castellanos, a National City police dispatcher. 
</P>
<P>
According to police, her mother, who had noticed a sudden weight loss by her 
daughter and had read about the case, confronted her Friday and persuaded her 
to come forward. 
</P>
<P>
The case of "Baby Girl Doe," as the authorities had dubbed her, had drawn the 
attention of the area news media last week. Earlier Friday, the county 
Department of Social Services had held a press conference displaying the baby, 
in hopes of finding her mother. 
</P>
<P>
Huggins gave birth at home, apparently without assistance, authorities said. An 
hour later, at 4:30 p.m., the baby was found outside the Pizza Hut restaurant 
in the 2000 block of Highland Avenue, where Huggins worked, said National City 
Police Sgt. Carey Sullivan. The police had had no luck finding the mother, said 
Sullivan. 
</P>
<P>
Although slightly dehydrated when found, the baby is healthy and eating well, 
said Heidi Staples, the county social worker supervising the case. The infant 
has been living with foster parents for the past week. 
</P>
<P>
The baby's case is now in juvenile court, which will probably take a year to 
decide who gets custody of the girl, said Carol Baenziger, a Department of 
Social Services spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes people panic when birth comes. They don't know what to do, and they 
just drop the baby and leave," said Raymond Fellers, deputy director of the 
department. 
</P>
<P>
Sullivan said National City has had two or three similar cases lately, and the 
parents of those children were located within a week or two. 
</P>
</TEXT>
