<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAX INCREASE: DEBATE OVER WHO WILL PAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
William Schneider wrote (Opinion, July 1) that the liberals in Congress are 
concerned about the kind of tax increase likely to be in the budget deal. "Last 
week, 134 House Democrats signed a letter to Foley . . . warning that they 
would not support any agreement with the White House that puts a further burden 
on (middle-income) families rather than the very wealthy." 
</P>
<P>
In the same issue, Robert L. Borosage (Commentary page) wrote that most of us 
are already paying a tax increase. Nine out of every 10 American families now 
pay more in federal taxes than they did before the Republicans took over the 
White House in 1980. Only the richest 10% enjoy a significant tax break. 
</P>
<P>
Robert Kuttner, writing in The Times (Nov. 13) pointed out that so much of our 
red ink comes from under-taxing the rich. Raising taxes of the nation's richest 
1% would raise about $130 billion in the nation's treasury. "Since 1977, before 
the supply-side revolution the top 1% of households had just 9.2% of the 
national income. Since 1977, the annual tax bill paid by the richest 1% has 
declined by about $50 billion a year, while their income, in real terms, has 
gone up by 74%." 
</P>
<P>
It isn't necessary for President Bush to raise taxes. He merely must return our 
income tax structure to 1970 levels when the wealthiest were paying their fair 
share. The trickle-down theory didn't work in the 1920s, and it certainly isn't 
working now. 
</P>
<P>
S.M. ROSEN 
</P>
<P>
Newbury Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
