<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRESERVING FRYMAN CANYON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Sierra Club has suggested that Fryman Canyon be a monument in order to 
preserve this unique piece of the Santa Monica Mountains' natural history, 
which contributed to the specific cultural history of the area in which this 
canyon exists. 
</P>
<P>
The people of our city have a right to access our cultural history in 
monuments, as well as books, and the city recognized this almost 20 years ago, 
for example, when Stoney Point Outcroppings in north Chatsworth was designated 
due to its being "one of the most picturesque areas in Los Angeles." 
</P>
<P>
This site is analogous to a giant redwood grove. Has familiarity blinded us? Is 
this one-of-a-kind remnant of our mountains' past natural state not worthy of 
our concern and protection? Or shall we guide it to extinction? 
</P>
<P>
SUSAN GENELIN 
</P>
<P>
Sherman Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070790-0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 243842 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 7, 1990, Saturday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 9; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
209 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
APPOINTED OFFICIALS SILENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Sherman Oaks Homeowners Assn. has been actively involved in trying to 
mitigate the scope of a three-story monolithic shopping center, encompassing 
one full city block, which is proposed for construction on Ventura Boulevard 
between Ventura Canyon Avenue and Woodman Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
We have had consistent acknowledgment and support from all of our elected 
officials throughout our campaign to fight this inappropriate intrusion into 
our neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
Namely, Councilmen Michael Woo and Zev Yaroslavsky, and City Atty. James Hahn. 
</P>
<P>
However, what is the score card for appointed officials? Zero. On April 18 our 
subcommittee for this project sent a four-page letter, along with almost 2,000 
signatures on a petition, to Mr. Kenneth Topping, director of planning in the 
Department of City Planning. This letter and the petition specifically 
addressed the issue of this Ventura-Woodman project and the vital environmental 
factors which we felt qualified the project for an Environmental Impact Report. 
This parcel was sent by certified mail. 
</P>
<P>
It has been more than two months and we have had absolutely no response 
whatsoever. 
</P>
<P>
Does this suggest an arrogance and irresponsibility on the part of appointed 
officials? 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD R. McCURDY 
</P>
<P>
Sherman Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
