<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIBERIAN REBELS SEIZE PORT NEAR DOE'S MANSION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MONROVIA, Liberia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rebels firing heavy artillery attacked the port of Monrovia and fought a sea 
battle Friday near the fortified mansion where Liberian President Samuel K. Doe 
is trying to cling to power with a crumbling army. 
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas moved in to the port, less than 2 miles from Doe's Atlantic beach 
fortress, telling soldiers to surrender, residents said. 
</P>
<P>
"Don't die for Doe," rebels told the demoralized and disorganized troops. 
</P>
<P>
One witness said he later saw three carloads of soldiers, dressed in civilian 
clothes, returning to central Monrovia, a city on a peninsula joined to the 
port by two bridges. 
</P>
<P>
Plumes of smoke from explosions rose from the city outskirts, and automatic 
rifle and artillery fire echoed across the besieged capital from dawn until 
noon. 
</P>
<P>
A rebel fishing trawler fired at a coast guard cutter about 5 miles offshore. 
The trawler, which hijacked a shipload of rice for the rebels Sunday, then gave 
chase, firing again before disappearing over the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
The United States, which has offered to evacuate Doe, supplied water to his 
mansion under heavy Marine guard. Four American vehicles, with black tinted 
windows, escorted a water tanker to the mansion, a witness said. 
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who invaded from Ivory Coast six months ago, now control all land 
routes out of the capital. 
</P>
<P>
Doe, who seized power in 1980, has declined a U.S. offer to help him leave 
Liberia as rebels led by his former associate, Charles Taylor, tighten their 
grip on Monrovia. 
</P>
<P>
Doe has offered to resign, on condition that his safety and that of his 
minority Krahn tribe is guaranteed. 
</P>
<P>
Washington has a task force of 2,300 Marines and four Navy ships off the coast 
to evacuate foreigners if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
Monrovia's 500,000 people spent much of Friday searching for food and carrying 
buckets of water from dwindling wells. The capital has been without water for 
nine days and without electricity for a week. 
</P>
<P>
Most shops and markets have been closed since Monday and some people have been 
begging for food, or foraging for leaves to eat from waste ground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
