<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
EUREKA; 
</P>
<P>
STATE CITES RARE BIRD IN REJECTING LOGGING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Pacific Lumber Co.'s plan to log 453 acres of old-growth timber in the 
Headwaters Forest near Eureka was rejected by the California Department of 
Forestry and Fire Protection. 
</P>
<P>
Department officials cited concerns for the rare marbled murrelet, a small 
robin-sized bird that nests in the tops of ancient redwood trees near the 
Pacific Ocean. The decision was the latest obstacle to Pacific Lumber's plans 
to log the 3,000 acres of virgin timber east of Eureka, known as the Headwaters 
Forest. A lawsuit by environmental groups has blocked the company from carrying 
out state-approved plans to cut 319 acres in the forest, the largest privately 
owned grove of ancient redwoods in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
