<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPIEGEL GETS STAY AGAINST ORDER TO DEPOSIT ASSETS; 
</P>
<P>
THRIFTS: THE EX-COLUMBIA S&amp;L CHIEF IS GRANTED A TEMPORARY REPRIEVE FROM 
PUTTING $19 MILLION OF RESTITUTIONS AND PENALTIES INTO AN ESCROW ACCOUNT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE KRENSAVAGE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thomas Spiegel, former Columbia Savings &amp; Loan chief executive, won a 
reprieve Friday from immediately depositing $19 million of restitutions and 
penalties into an escrow account. 
</P>
<P>
But in granting the reprieve, U.S. District Judge Stephen V. Wilson in Los 
Angeles froze the assets of Spiegel and his wife, and required him to post a 
$1-million bond by next Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
In a two-hour hearing, Spiegel's attorneys successfully challenged an order 
issued Thursday by the Office of Thrift Supervision that would have required 
Spiegel to place the funds and his Columbia stock in an escrow account by noon 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The order was part of the largest civil complaint ever filed by S&amp;L 
regulators against an individual. In that administrative complaint, the OTS on 
Thursday charged Spiegel with improperly diverting $19 million of the thrift's 
funds to pay himself hefty bonuses, buy luxury planes, a gun collection and 
condominiums, among other allegations. The OTS also moved to levy a $5-million 
fine against Spiegel for burdening the Beverly Hills-based S&amp;L with losses. 
</P>
<P>
Spiegel's attorneys challenged the applicability of the laws on which the OTS 
based its complaint. They argued that those laws apply only to current S&amp;L 
officers. Spiegel resigned as Columbia's chief in December and since then has 
severed all direct management ties to the thrift. 
</P>
<P>
Spiegel's attorneys also argued that regulators failed to give the former 
executive a fair hearing. 
</P>
<P>
"They've been conducting an investigation for more than seven months and 
they've provided no explanation as to why it was necessary to act as 
precipitously as they did," Spiegel attorney Dennis Perluss said after the 
hearing. "They filed their charges without giving us any advance notice. They 
provided no justification for the cease-and-desist order." 
</P>
<P>
In granting Spiegel a temporary restraining order, Wilson said the balance of 
hardships in the case "tips strongly" in favor of the former Columbia chief. 
Wilson said Spiegel must notify the government 48 hours in advance of any 
expense he incurs of more than $5,000, excluding attorneys' fees or 
"reasonable" living expenses, and that such expenditures can be challenged in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
The judge said Spiegel and his wife could not "transfer, sell, encumber or 
otherwise dissipate" assets, including transferring them outside the country. 
</P>
<P>
Wilson scheduled a July 30 hearing to explore regulators' charges. Both sides 
are required to file court papers in the case no later than July 16, he ruled. 
</P>
<P>
Harris Weinstein, chief counsel for OTS, said after the hearing that "the OTS 
is pleased the judge has placed significant constraints on the ability of Mr. 
and Mrs. Spiegel to use and move their assets while the matter is under court 
consideration." 
</P>
<P>
However, the judge denied an OTS request that the Spiegels file with the court 
a statement disclosing their assets. Weinstein said that denial could hinder 
efforts to enforce the freeze. 
</P>
<P>
"It's always harder when you have to go back and reconstruct assets as of a 
certain date," Weinstein said. 
</P>
<P>
Spiegel, in a written statement, called Wilson's order "fair and reasonable." 
</P>
<P>
Spiegel and his family control about two-thirds of Columbia stock. But those 
securities are virtually worthless, as the thrift has posted huge losses during 
the past year, in part because of the decline in value of its $3-billion 
portfolio of risky junk bonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Thomas Spiegel Los Angeles Times 
</P>
