<HEADLINE>
<P>
A NIGHT OF MUSICAL HORROR AND CRUDITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE BOEHM, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LAGUNA BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If you don't have any ideas, try a gimmick. 
</P>
<P>
That seems to be the principle behind Johnny Monster and the Nightmares. The 
San Clemente band has gained some popularity on the local rock circuit by 
taking musical styles and a coarse, rowdy attitude that come straight from the 
frat house, and relocating them to the haunted house. 
</P>
<P>
The four-member schlock-horror band's show Wednesday night at Club Postnuclear 
was a monstrous mishmash, just the sort of mutation of entertainment you get 
when a gimmick goes groping around without an idea in its head. 
</P>
<P>
The gimmick, in this case, seems to be to reincarnate the nasty but funny ghoul 
of "Beetlejuice" as a farcical rock singer. But achieving that would require a 
front man with the imagination and acting ability to forge a true persona 
incorporating some snide wit. Acting was beyond Johnny Monster (his real name 
is David Paskowitz). Even parody would require more consideration than this 
band could muster. About all this Monster could manage was crude horsing 
around. 
</P>
<P>
The fact that Paskowitz horses around with a good deal of energy may account 
for the band's having found an audience. The wiry singer often jumped onto the 
floor with the pit denizens, slam-dancing with abandon as the band thrashed 
away punk-style. The physical contact took a more worrisome turn when Paskowitz 
pinned a woman in the audience to the floor in imitation of a sexual assault. 
All in good fun, right? Just a stage buffoon making like he's Mr. Hyde? Maybe, 
but what if the next person Paskowitz tackles doesn't see the joke, the way his 
unsuspecting Postnuclear victim apparently did? 
</P>
<P>
The musical side of the routine called for Paskowitz to bellow theatrically in 
imitation of Vincent Price while delivering inane verses on mock-ghoulish 
themes that got no better than this: 
</P>
<P>
 Going to a lifeless luau 
</P>
<P>
 You're a corpse, you're invited. 
</P>
<P>
 Going to a lifeless luau 
</P>
<P>
 Where the dead get excited. 
</P>
<P>
Paskowitz does have a capacious set of pipes, and he frequently showed off his 
lung power with falsetto screams that most heavy-metal bleaters would envy. At 
certain moments, he generated some force, leading one to think there might be a 
real rock singer underneath all that melodramatic Grand Guignol posing and 
mannered B-movie vocal phrasing. 
</P>
<P>
It was hard to tell whether there was potentially a real rock band under the 
blanket of stage smoke and sonic murk that tends to envelope Postnuclear. When 
audible, guitarist John Fields spun out a tuneless metallic screech, while 
drummer Sean Spencer and bassist Shane Anderson played to garage-band standards 
on songs that borrowed from surf music and R&amp;B. 
</P>
<P>
Tender Fury was by far the more rewarding band on this double-bill. Singer Jack 
Grisham is no stranger to stage gimmickry, dating back to the early 1980s, when 
he fronted the original T.S.O.L. (which, incidentally, managed in the 
necrophiliac fantasy, "Code Blue," to convey the sort of crude but pointedly 
satiric wit that eludes Johnny Monster). Grisham resorted to one of his old 
tricks midway through the half-hour set, lowering his pants a la Jim Morrison 
to reveal his leopard-spotted underwear. But he quickly hitched up his trousers 
and got on with the show. 
</P>
<P>
Grisham's singing was drowned out in a poor mix through most of the show, 
emerging only on the last two numbers. While he never has had the bite and 
power of a top-grade rock singer, Grisham compensates with personality that 
comes through in his theatrical, almost vaudevillian drawl. In the past, he has 
sometimes taken shows as a lark, joking his way through performances. But 
Grisham, who says he has changed old ways by quitting substance abuse, 
performed with focus and intensity. 
</P>
<P>
It was the playing, rather than the singing, that carried this performance. 
Hunt Sales, the drummer from David Bowie's band, Tin Machine, kept up a fast, 
fiery pace (Sales, who produced Tender Fury's current album, "Garden of Evil," 
has been sitting in as the band's stage drummer since early this year). 
Guitarist Daniel Root stayed in step with Sales, churning out hard, slab-like 
riffs and feedback-drenched solos. On Tender Fury's two albums, Root excels 
with forceful economy. He showed that he could stretch out more prolifically on 
stage without becoming diffuse. 
</P>
<P>
The sound mix improved at the end, in time for Tender Fury to finish with two 
driving numbers, "Garden of Evil" and "(Desperate) And Looking for the Chip," 
that recalled the Cult in their headlong, insistent throb. Tender Fury 
headlined Friday at Bogart's in Long Beach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Johnny Monster (a.k.a. David Paskowitz) and the Nightmares perform rock 
show at Club Postnuclear. ROD BOREN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
