<HEADLINE>
<P>
REVIEW OF ERASURE CONCERT HARPED ON SEXUALITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After reading your review of the Erasure concert ("Capering Andy Bell Leads 
Erasure Through Zesty Evening" by Mike Boehm, Calendar June 18), I was pretty 
upset. For me and for three good friends of mine, this was our first concert, 
and we were very excited. Naturally, our hopes were high for this concert, and 
Erasure proved very quickly to be a very enthusiastic group. The four of us, as 
well as many others at the concert, knew of the two men's homosexuality. That 
had absolutely no effect whatsoever on our feelings toward the music or the 
band. 
</P>
<P>
Erasure's performance was nothing short of awesome. Maybe I feel this way 
because this was my first concert, but I'm almost positive that I really 
enjoyed the concert to the fullest. 
</P>
<P>
One of the most eye-catching lines in the article is this: "Bell didn't make a 
big point of his sexuality. . . ." I (also) didn't feel that Andy Bell made any 
special attempts to "exploit" his sexuality. In your article, however, there 
was one basic theme that you seemed to revolve around: Bell's sexuality! Your 
review didn't seem to be much of a review. It was more along the lines of gay 
performers and how much straight people love to see them perform. 
</P>
<P>
I think that most of the people there were able to overlook the sexuality of 
the two singers and enjoy the concert. It was neat. Nobody was making 
derogatory remarks that are usually heard when there are a couple of gay people 
around. I don't believe that I lowered my guard for the fun that they provided, 
and I'd like to believe that the other 10,000 there didn't either. 
</P>
<P>
You did Erasure an injustice by your constant harping on their homosexuality. 
If you went to a concert to later offer a review, please do that. Don't stoop 
to the level of bigotry that a lot of society has. Offer your readers an 
evaluation of the concert and Erasure's wonderful ability to give a stage 
performance that kids and adults will never forget. Please don't make such a 
big deal about their choice of life. 
</P>
<P>
LESLIE CARR 
</P>
<P>
Huntington Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
